docs.abstract: Mr. Jones, from deeply conservative Alabama, is the Senate’s most vulnerable Democratic incumbent. But far from tiptoeing toward re-election, he seems almost liberated by his predicament.
docs.snippet: Mr. Jones, from deeply conservative Alabama, is the Senate’s most vulnerable Democratic incumbent. But far from tiptoeing toward re-election, he seems almost liberated by his predicament.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Politically endangered lawmakers about to face voters often find themselves tempering their instincts, breaking with their parties on tough votes to prove independence and placate constituents, and offering mealy-mouthed platitudes on the most divisive topics of the day.

headline.main: Fighting an Uphill Senate Re-election Battle, Doug Jones Does It His Way

docs.abstract: The comedy site, a conservative answer to ‘The Onion,’ used to have Trump squarely in its cross hairs. But now it’s less about him and more about the people who can’t stand him.

docs.lead_paragraph: Four years ago, in the heat of the Republican primary, a fledgling satire site jabbed at the party’s leading contender: “Psychopathic Megalomaniac Somehow Garnering Evangelical Vote.” The story proceeded to describe Donald Trump as “a man who would seemingly have no qualms obliterating hundreds of thousands of people for purely egotistical reasons.”

docs.abstract: The star of the Australian police drama “Mystery Road” harks back to the rugged icons of old westerns. He is also Aboriginal, which makes the role more complicated — and rare.
docs.snippet: The star of the Australian police drama “Mystery Road” harks back to the rugged icons of old westerns. He is also Aboriginal, which makes the role more complicated — and rare.
docs.lead_paragraph: Hat, boots, holster. Furrowed brow and taciturn demeanor. The grizzled, bearded detective Jay Swan may hail from Down Under and travel in an S.U.V. instead of a horse, but he is an immediately recognizable archetype — straight out of a Hollywood western.

headline.main: Aaron Pedersen Is a Different Kind of Archetypal Leading Man

docs.abstract: The playwright whips up a virtual ensemble of eccentrics, but his vision feels out of step with the moment.
docs.snippet: The playwright whips up a virtual ensemble of eccentrics, but his vision feels out of step with the moment.
docs.lead_paragraph: Quick etymology lesson: The word utopia comes from the Greek. It means “no place.” So maybe it makes sense that Charles L. Mee’s new play “Utopia,” produced by San Francisco’s Cutting Ball Theater and streaming through Nov. 15, feels so untethered. A whimsical ensemble drama, a dance performance and an online gallery show, it is so dissevered from the terrestrial that it melts into pixelated air.

headline.main: ‘Utopia’ Review: Charles L. Mee’s New Play Is a Frothy Escape
headline.print_headline: Frothy Morsels of Escape Teeter a Bit Out of Step
